  "proof_sketch": "Given dim2=256 and block_size perturbed to 255 (likely), the original kernel computes elements_per_thread = (256+255-1)/255 = 2, covering all 256 elements. The mutant computes 2-1=1, covering only indices 0..254 (255 elements). The last element (index 255) is never processed. Therefore, the output differs only when the maximum value in a reduction slice resides at index 255 and is strictly greater than all other values in that slice.",
  "survival_reason": "Previous tests used random input values where the maximum per slice was rarely at the last element. The 'boundary_last_element' stress test may have set a large value at the last element, but if a larger value appeared elsewhere in the same slice, the mutant still produced the correct max. Since the mutation only omits the last element, the output matches the original unless the max is uniquely at that position. The 112 random rounds and 45 stress rounds did not guarantee this specific condition for every slice simultaneously, so the mutant survived.",
  "killable": true,
  "kill_strategy": "Create an input where for every reduction slice over dim2, the maximum value is exclusively at the last index (255), and all preceding values are strictly smaller. For example, fill the tensor with -1.0 and set the last element of each slice to 1.0. The original kernel will output 1.0, while the mutant kernel will output -1.0 for all slices, producing a bitwise difference.",
  "suggested_test": {
    "description": "Input with constant low value (-1.0) except the last element of each dim2 slice (index 255) set to a high value (1.0), ensuring the maximum is uniquely at the missed position. This targets the off-by-one bug caused by block size perturbation.",
    "python_code": "def generate_inputs(device):\n    import torch\n    x = torch.full((16, 256, 256), -1.0, dtype=torch.float32, device=device)\n    x[:, :, -1] = 1.0\n    return [x]"
  },
  "recommendations": "Always include boundary tests where the extreme value (max or min) is placed at the very last element of the reduction dimension, especially when the number of threads is not a divisor of the dimension size. Also, test with block sizes that are not multiples of the reduction dimension to catch off-by-one errors."
